05203nam a22010455i 9780228009757DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280097577 a10.1515/97802280097572doi  a(DE-B1597)657032  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX2380b.L36 2021 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a253/.209442231 aLane, Christopher J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCallings and Consequences :bThe Making of Catholic Vocational Culture in Early Modern France /cChristopher J. Lane. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tBefore the Rigorist Turn: The Catholic Reformation of Vocation in the Long Sixteenth Century -- tUrgency: Vocational Rigorism and the Dangers of Choosing Poorly -- tInclusiveness: Lay Vocation in a Rigorist Framework -- tMethod: Systematizing the Discernment Process -- tLiberty: Parental Involvement without Parental Coercion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of vocation in an early modern setting calls to mind the priesthood or religious life in a monastery or cloister; to be “called” by God meant to leave the concerns of the world behind. Beginning in the mid-seventeenth century, French Catholic clergy began to promote the innovative idea that everyone, even an ordinary layperson, was called to a vocation or “state of life” and that discerning this call correctly had implications for one’s happiness and salvation, and for the social good.In Callings and Consequences Christopher Lane analyzes the origins, growth, and influence of a culture of vocation that became a central component of the Catholic Reformation and its legacy in France. The reformers’ new vision of the choice of a state of life was marked by four characteristics: urgency (the realization that one’s soul was at stake), inclusiveness (the belief that everyone, including lay people, was called by God), method (the use of proven discernment practices), and liberty (the belief that this choice must be free from coercion, especially by parents). No mere passing phenomena, these vocational reforms engendered enduring beliefs and practices within the repertoire of global Catholic modernity, even to the present day.An illuminating and sometimes surprising history of pastoral reform, Callings and Consequences helps us to understand the history of Catholic vocational culture and its role in the modernizing process, within Christianity and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aReformationzFrance. 0aVocationxCatholic ChurchxHistory of doctrines. 0aVocation, EcclesiasticalxHistory of doctrines. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aCharles Taylor.  aChristianity.  aCounter-Reformation.  aEuropean.  aFrancis de Sales.  aFrench.  aIgnatian.  aIgnatius Loyola.  aJansenist.  aOld Regime.  aReformation.  aancien regime.  aauthority.  aclergy.  aclerical.  acoercion.  aconfessionalization.  adevotion.  adevout.  adiscernment.  aeducation.  aetat de vie.  afreedom.  agrace.  ainclusive.  alaity.  alayman.  aliberty.  amarriage.  amethod.  amodernity.  amonastic.  amoralism.  apastoral.  apatriarchal.  apiety.  apriesthood.  arationalization.  areligious.  arigorist.  asalvation.  astate life.  asystematization.  avows.  ayouth.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228009757?locatt=mod